CleanPlate — Secure Roommate Chore Coordinator
==============================================

Standard library only. No pip install required.
Requires Python 3.10+.

Platform: macOS / Linux.


OVERVIEW
--------

CleanPlate now runs as a shell-wrapped client/server CLI:

- `python3 main.py serve` starts the HTTP API server
- `./cleanplate` or `python3 main.py interactive` opens the interactive client shell
- commands entered in the shell are parsed locally, then sent to the server
- the server owns the database and runs the business logic

This means your normal workflow is:

1. start the server in one terminal
2. open the CleanPlate shell in another terminal
3. run all app commands inside `cleanplate>`


QUICK START
-----------

  # Terminal 1: start the server
  export CLEANPLATE_AUDIT_HMAC_KEY='replace-with-a-long-random-secret'
  export CLEANPLATE_USERNAME_HMAC_KEY='replace-with-a-second-long-random-secret'
  python3 main.py serve

  # Terminal 2: open the client shell
  ./cleanplate

  cleanplate> register --username alice
  cleanplate> login --username alice
  cleanplate> household create --name "42 Elm Street"
  cleanplate> household list
  cleanplate> exit


INTERACTIVE SHELL
-----------------

Open the client shell with either:

  ./cleanplate

or:

  python3 main.py interactive

Inside the shell:

- type `help` to show the command tree
- type `exit`, `quit`, or `q` to leave
- omitted values are prompted for on many commands
- shorthand phrases are normalized into the structured command form

Examples:

  cleanplate> register alice
  cleanplate> login alice
  cleanplate> whoami
  cleanplate> household create "Maple House"
  cleanplate> household join aB3xQr_kLmN
  cleanplate> chore create 1 "Take out trash"
  cleanplate> chore reschedule 4 --due 2026-04-20
  cleanplate> activity complete 4
  cleanplate> activity incomplete 4
  cleanplate> help
  cleanplate> exit

By default the client connects to `http://127.0.0.1:8000`.
To use a different server, set `CLEANPLATE_SERVER_URL`.

Local sessions are client-side files. By default they are terminal-scoped when
possible, so different terminals can stay logged in separately. You can also
override the session location with:

- `CLEANPLATE_SESSION_NAME`
- `CLEANPLATE_SESSION_PATH`


COMMAND REFERENCE
-----------------

Run these inside the `cleanplate>` prompt.

Common shorthand examples:

  register alice
  login alice
  reset-password alice
  forgot-password alice
  recover-password alice TOKEN_HERE
  household create "Maple House"
  household join aB3xQr_kLmN
  household show 1
  chore create 1 "Take out trash"
  chore assign 4 bob
  chore list 1
  chore show 4
  chore reschedule 4 --due 2026-04-20
  activity complete 4
  activity incomplete 4
  activity dispute 4 --reason "Still dirty"
  activity audit 1


Identity & Access
-----------------

  register         [--username <name>]
  login            [--username <name>]
  reset-password   [--username <name>]
  forgot-password  [--username <name>]
  recover-password [--username <name>] [--token <reset_token>]
  logout
  whoami

Notes:

- `reset-password` is for a user who knows their current password
- `forgot-password` issues a one-time recovery token
- `recover-password` uses that token to set a new password


Household Management
--------------------

  household create        [--name "42 Elm St"]
  household join          [--code <invite_code>]
  household show          [--id <household_id>]
  household list
  household rotate-invite [--id <household_id>]
  household remove-member [--id <household_id>] [--username <name>]


Chore Management
----------------

  chore create     [--household <id>] [--title "Take out trash"] [--description "..."] [--due YYYY-MM-DD] [--assign <name>]...
  chore assign     [--chore <id>] [--username <name>]
  chore list       [--household <id>] [--status pending|complete|disputed] [--mine] [--overdue]
  chore show       [--chore <id>]
  chore reschedule [--chore <id>] [--due YYYY-MM-DD]

Notes:

- chore titles are not treated as globally unique; recurring chores can reuse a name
- chores can have multiple assignees
- `chore reschedule` can both add a first due date and change an existing one


Activity & Completion
---------------------

  activity complete   [--chore <id>]
  activity incomplete [--chore <id>]
  activity dispute    [--chore <id>] [--reason "..."]
  activity resolve    [--complaint <id>] [--outcome uphold|dismiss] [--note "..."]
  activity audit      [--household <id>]
  activity poll

Notes:

- any assigned roommate can mark a shared chore complete
- assigned roommates and admins can also mark a completed chore back to `pending`
- disputes remain available for “redo” and complaint resolution workflows


EXAMPLE WALKTHROUGH
-------------------

  # Terminal 1
  python3 main.py serve

  # Terminal 2
  ./cleanplate

  cleanplate> register alice
  cleanplate> register bob

  cleanplate> login alice
  cleanplate> household create "42 Elm Street"
  # -> prints invite code, e.g. "Invite code: aB3xQr_kLmN"

  cleanplate> login bob
  cleanplate> household join aB3xQr_kLmN

  cleanplate> login alice
  cleanplate> chore create 1 "Vacuum living room" --due 2026-04-10 --assign bob --assign alice

  cleanplate> login bob
  cleanplate> activity complete 1

  cleanplate> login alice
  cleanplate> activity incomplete 1
  cleanplate> chore reschedule 1 --due 2026-04-17
  cleanplate> activity audit 1
  cleanplate> exit


FILE LAYOUT
-----------

  cleanplate        Shell wrapper that launches the interactive client
  main.py           Entry point for the server and interactive shell
  client_cli.py     Client-side shell handlers and parser wiring
  api_client.py     JSON/HTTP client helper
  api_server.py     HTTP transport and server-side command dispatch
  db.py             SQLite schema and query helpers
  session.py        Local client session storage and request-scoped session override
  auth.py           Registration, login, password reset/recovery
  households.py     Household creation, joining, invites, membership
  chores.py         Chore creation, assignment, listing, rescheduling
  activity.py       Completion, incompletion, disputes, audit log, notifications
  cleanplate.db     Created automatically on first run


ARCHITECTURE
------------

Client shell:

- `./cleanplate` or `python3 main.py interactive`
- parses commands locally
- prompts for missing inputs
- sends requests to the API server
- stores the local session file

Server:

- `python3 main.py serve`
- receives JSON requests over HTTP
- dispatches them to the feature modules
- owns all database access

Feature modules:

- `auth.py`, `households.py`, `chores.py`, and `activity.py`
- contain the actual business logic, validation, role checks, and audit writes

Database:

- SQLite via `db.py`
- accessed only on the server side


SECURITY NOTES
--------------

Passwords:

- stored with `scrypt`
- password strength checks reject common, sequential, and weak passwords

Usernames:

- stored as HMAC-SHA256 digests at rest
- human-readable usernames are kept separately as `display_name`
- server key must come from `CLEANPLATE_USERNAME_HMAC_KEY`
- `USERNAME_HMAC_KEY` is also accepted for compatibility

Password recovery:

- recovery uses one-time reset tokens stored as hashes
- tokens expire after 15 minutes
- prototype mode currently prints the token instead of sending email

Audit log:

- HMAC-SHA256 chained
- `verify_chain()` detects tampering
- server key must come from `CLEANPLATE_AUDIT_HMAC_KEY`
- `AUDIT_HMAC_KEY` is also accepted for compatibility

Sessions:

- stored locally on the client side
- expire automatically after the configured TTL in `session.py`
- cleared on logout

Authorization:

- role checks happen inside the command handlers, not just at login

Multi-household support:

- a single user can belong to multiple households
- membership is tracked per `(user_id, household_id)`
